    "summary": "The Founding of Constantinople (dedicated May 11, 330 AD) by Emperor Constantine on the site of the Greek colony of [[event:1990|Foundation of Byzantium]] Byzantium was one of the most consequential acts of city-founding in history — the creation of 'New Rome' on the Bosphorus that would serve as the capital of the Roman Empire, the Byzantine Empire, and eventually the Ottoman Empire for over a millennium. Constantine recognized that the old city of Rome was geographically peripheral to an empire increasingly threatened on its eastern and northern frontiers, and chose the Bosphorus for its unparalleled strategic position.\n\nConstantine modeled his new city on Rome: it had its own Senate, seven hills, fourteen administrative districts, a Forum, a Hippodrome (chariot-racing track seating 100,000), and a palace complex. He filled it with art looted from pagan temples across the empire — including the famous Serpent Column from Delphi, still standing in Istanbul. The city was embellished over centuries to become the most magnificent in the medieval world: the Hagia Sophia (completed 537 AD), the massive land walls (completed 413 AD, never breached until 1453), and the Golden Horn harbor combined natural and artificial defenses of extraordinary effectiveness. Constantinople's fall to the Ottoman Turks under Mehmed II in 1453 ended the Byzantine Empire and triggered the flight of Greek scholars to Italy that catalyzed the Renaissance.",
